<percentage>0</percentage></teachingTypeInCurriculum></teachingTypesInCurriculumYear></programCurriculum><programDescriptions><contentLink><contentSummary xml:lang="en"><![CDATA[Students become experts in innovation processes of mathematics and science curricula at all levels of education and are trained in the integration of ICT and in development of communication skills.]]></contentSummary><contentType>website</contentType><subject>objectives</subject><webLink xml:lang="en"><![CDATA[http://studieadres.nl]]></webLink></contentLink><contentLink><contentSummary xml:lang="en"><![CDATA[Multimedia and education; teaching, learning and communication; education policy and curriculum. Students practise ICT applications in education, design materials, and develop research projects.]]></contentSummary><contentType>website</contentType><subject>curriculum</subject><webLink xml:lang="en"><![CDATA[http://studieadres.nl]]></webLink></contentLink><contentLink><contentSummary xml:lang="en"><![CDATA[Seminars and workshops are conducted in a collegial format of advising, reflecting, and learning by all participants, including staff. Activities centre on participants' own cultures and experiences.]]></contentSummary><contentType>website</contentType><subject>instruction modes</subject><webLink xml:lang="en"><![CDATA[http://studieadres.nl]]></webLink></contentLink><programDescription xml:lang="en"><![CDATA[The Programme in Mathematics and Science education trains students to become experts in the innovation process of Mathematics and Science curricula and pedagogy at all levels of education, with emphasis on the integration of ICT.

The programme is characterised by an interdisciplinary approach, and students come from a range of disciplines including Biology, Chemistry, Computer Science, Mathematics and Physics. Each student completes an individualised programme based on their 'specialty science discipline', their area of study in their previous degree. 

This approach allows the student to both deepen their previous knowledge during their Master's studies, and to locate that knowledge within an interdisciplinary context. 
